    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should men over 40 take creatine?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes — creatine is one of the most well-researched supplements available and has meaningful benefits for men over 40, including improved muscle strength, faster recovery, and cognitive benefits that are particularly relevant as men age. However, creatine works as a multiplier on top of adequate protein intake. Men over 40 who are eating less than 100–120g of protein daily will see far greater benefit from fixing their protein first than from adding creatine to a protein-deficient diet."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much creatine should men over 40 take?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The research-backed dose is 3–5g of creatine monohydrate per day, taken consistently. There is no need for a loading phase — daily supplementation at 3–5g reaches saturation within 3–4 weeks. Creatine monohydrate is the most studied form and the one with the strongest evidence base. More expensive forms (creatine HCL, buffered creatine) have not been shown to outperform monohydrate."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does creatine help with brain function after 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes — emerging research suggests creatine has meaningful cognitive benefits, particularly for older adults. The brain uses creatine as an energy substrate, and supplementation has been associated with improvements in memory, mental fatigue, and processing speed. A 2023 meta-analysis found that creatine supplementation improved memory performance in healthy adults, with the effect size increasing with age — making it particularly relevant for men over 40."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can creatine replace protein for building muscle?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No — creatine and protein serve completely different functions. Protein provides the amino acids your muscles use to repair and grow. Creatine enhances the energy system that powers muscular effort. Without adequate protein, there is no raw material for muscle repair regardless of creatine intake. Creatine amplifies the benefit of training — but only if protein is supplying the building blocks your muscles need to respond to that training."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is creatine safe for men over 40?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes — creatine monohydrate has one of the strongest safety profiles of any supplement. Decades of research show no adverse effects on kidney function in healthy adults at recommended doses. Men with existing kidney disease should consult a physician, but for healthy men over 40, creatine at 3–5g daily is well-tolerated. The main side effect is mild water retention in muscle tissue during the first few weeks of use."
        }
      }
    ]
