    <!-- QUICK ANSWER -->
    <div class="quick-answer">
      <h2>The Short Answer</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Yes — creatine is legitimate and men over 40 have <strong>more to gain from it than younger men</strong></li>
        <li>Benefits include improved strength, faster recovery, and <strong>measurable cognitive improvements</strong></li>
        <li>The dose is simple: <strong>3–5g of creatine monohydrate daily</strong>, no loading phase needed</li>
        <li>But creatine is a <strong>multiplier, not a foundation</strong> — it amplifies what's already working</li>
        <li><strong>If you're under-eating protein, fix that first.</strong> Creatine on top of a protein deficit is optimizing the wrong thing</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <p>I'm 64. I've watched a lot of men my age reach for creatine — and fish oil, and testosterone boosters, and whatever else the supplement aisle is pushing this month — while eating 60g of protein a day and wondering why they're still losing muscle.</p>

    <p>I'm not here to tell you creatine doesn't work. It does. The research on creatine is some of the most consistent in all of sports science, and the benefits for men over 40 specifically are real and worth knowing about. But there's a reason most guys don't get the results they expect from it — and it has nothing to do with which brand they bought or whether they loaded.</p>

    <p>They're trying to optimize a system that isn't built yet.</p>

