      </div>
    </div>

    <h2>What Creatine Actually Does</h2>

    <p>Creatine is not a protein. It doesn't provide amino acids or directly build muscle. What it does is regenerate ATP — the energy currency your muscles use during high-intensity effort. When your muscles run out of ATP mid-set, creatine phosphate donates a phosphate group to rebuild it faster, extending the window before fatigue sets in.</p>

    <p>In practical terms: you can push harder, recover faster between sets, and sustain more training volume over time. That additional training stimulus, combined with adequate protein and recovery, is what produces more muscle over months and years. Creatine doesn't build muscle directly — it enables you to do more of the work that builds muscle.</p>

