        <div class="benefit-icon">💪</div>
        <div class="benefit-title">Strength & Power Output</div>
        <div class="benefit-desc">Consistently improves performance in resistance training — more reps, more sets, more stimulus over time.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="benefit-card">
        <div class="benefit-icon">⚡</div>
        <div class="benefit-title">Recovery Between Sets</div>
        <div class="benefit-desc">Faster ATP regeneration means shorter rest periods and less fatigue accumulation during training sessions.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="benefit-card">
        <div class="benefit-icon">🧠</div>
        <div class="benefit-title">Cognitive Function</div>
        <div class="benefit-desc">The brain uses creatine as an energy substrate. Supplementation improves memory and reduces mental fatigue — especially relevant after 40.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="benefit-card">
        <div class="benefit-icon">🛡️</div>
        <div class="benefit-title">Muscle Preservation</div>
        <div class="benefit-desc">Research shows creatine helps attenuate age-related muscle loss, making it a meaningful tool for men over 40 fighting sarcopenia.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- COGNITION BOX -->
    <div class="cognition-box">
      <div class="cog-label">The Benefit Most Men Don't Know About</div>
      <h3>Creatine and Brain Health After 40</h3>
      <p>The cognitive angle on creatine is underreported and genuinely surprising. The brain is metabolically expensive — it consumes roughly 20% of your body's energy — and it uses creatine as a key energy reserve. As men age, brain creatine levels decline alongside muscle creatine. A 2023 meta-analysis found that creatine supplementation significantly improved memory performance in healthy adults, with the effect size being larger in older adults than younger ones. For men over 40 noticing slower recall or more mental fatigue, this is a legitimate, research-backed benefit — not supplement marketing.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>What Most Guys Get Wrong</h2>

    <p>Here's the part that doesn't get said enough.</p>

    <p>Creatine is a performance multiplier. It amplifies the results of a system that's already working. If you're training consistently and eating enough protein to support muscle repair and growth, creatine gives that system a meaningful boost. If you're not — if your protein is chronically low, if your training is inconsistent, if you're eating 70g of protein a day and wondering why your muscle isn't responding — creatine is not going to change the outcome.</p>

    <!-- WHAT MOST GUYS MISS BOX -->
    <div class="miss-box">
      <div class="miss-label">What Most Guys Miss</div>
      <h3>Creatine Is a Multiplier. Protein Is the Foundation.</h3>
      <p>Think of it this way. Creatine is a high-performance fuel additive. It makes a well-built engine run better. But if the engine is running on fumes — if you're under-eating protein and your muscles don't have the raw material they need to repair and grow — you're just adding a premium additive to a car that's already broken down.</p>
      <p>Protein provides the amino acids your muscles use to rebuild after training. <strong>Without adequate protein, there is nothing for creatine to amplify.</strong> The training stimulus happens. The muscle damage happens. The repair signal goes out. And then the materials aren't there to answer it.</p>
      <p>Most men over 40 are eating 60–80g of protein a day — 40 to 60g short of what the research suggests for muscle maintenance. If that's you, the most powerful thing you can do right now isn't adding creatine. It's <strong>closing the protein gap first</strong>. Get your foundation solid. Then creatine becomes a genuine accelerant on top of something that's actually working.</p>
    </div>

