    <h2>Cutting Through the Noise: What the Research Actually Shows</h2>

    <p>Creatine has been studied for decades and the consensus is unusually clear — but that hasn't stopped a lot of myths from circulating. Here's the straight verdict on the most common ones.</p>

    <div style="overflow-x:auto; margin: 28px 0 40px;">
      <table style="width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:0.9rem;">
        <thead>
          <tr style="background:var(--charcoal);">
            <th style="padding:12px 16px; color:#fff; font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif; font-weight:700; text-align:left; border-bottom:2px solid var(--green-light);">The Claim</th>
            <th style="padding:12px 16px; color:#fff; font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif; font-weight:700; text-align:left; border-bottom:2px solid var(--green-light);">Verdict</th>
            <th style="padding:12px 16px; color:#fff; font-family:'Plus Jakarta Sans',sans-serif; font-weight:700; text-align:left; border-bottom:2px solid var(--green-light);">What the Research Says</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:600; color:var(--charcoal);">"It causes muscle growth directly"</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:700; color:#92400e;">Indirect only</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; color:var(--muted);">Creatine improves training output, which drives muscle growth — but only if protein supplies the building blocks for repair.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--cream);">
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:600; color:var(--charcoal);">"It burns fat"</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:700; color:#b91c1c;">No</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; color:var(--muted);">No direct effect on fat oxidation or metabolic rate. It helps preserve muscle during a caloric deficit, which indirectly supports body composition.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:600; color:var(--charcoal);">"It makes you look bloated"</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:700; color:#92400e;">Mostly myth</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; color:var(--muted);">It draws water into muscle cells — which makes muscles look fuller, not bloated. Subcutaneous water retention is rare at standard doses.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border); background:var(--cream);">
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:600; color:var(--charcoal);">"It damages your kidneys"</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:700; color:var(--green);">False</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; color:var(--muted);">20+ years of research show no adverse effect on kidney function in healthy adults at 3–5g daily. Consult a doctor if you have existing kidney disease.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="border-bottom:1px solid var(--border);">
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:600; color:var(--charcoal);">"You need to load it"</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:700; color:#b91c1c;">No</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; color:var(--muted);">Loading (20g/day for a week) reaches saturation faster but isn't necessary. 5g daily reaches the same saturation point within 3–4 weeks.</td>
          </tr>
          <tr style="background:var(--cream);">
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:600; color:var(--charcoal);">"It can replace protein"</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; font-weight:700; color:#b91c1c;">No</td>
            <td style="padding:12px 16px; color:var(--muted);">Completely different mechanisms. Protein builds. Creatine powers. You need both — in that order.</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2>The Right Order of Operations</h2>

    <p>If you want to get the most out of creatine — and everything else — the sequence matters.</p>

    <div class="order-steps">
      <div class="order-step">
        <div class="step-num">1</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <div class="step-title">Hit your protein target consistently</div>
          <p class="step-desc">For most men over 40, that's 100–130g per day, spread across 3–4 meals. Use the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/protein-calculator-men-over-40/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">protein calculator</a> to find your specific number. This is the non-negotiable foundation. Without it, nothing else works as intended. If you want to see what that actually looks like in real food, the <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/" style="color:var(--green);font-weight:600;">120g visual breakdown</a> is the clearest reference on this site.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="order-step">
        <div class="step-num">2</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <div class="step-title">Train consistently — 3+ sessions per week</div>
          <p class="step-desc">Creatine amplifies training stimulus. Without consistent resistance training, there's no stimulus to amplify. You don't need an elaborate program — but you need to show up regularly.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="order-step">
        <div class="step-num">3</div>
        <div class="step-content">
          <div class="step-title">Add creatine as an accelerant</div>
          <p class="step-desc">Once protein and training are consistent, 3–5g of creatine monohydrate daily is a legitimate and well-supported addition. At this point you're adding fuel to a fire that's already burning — and you'll actually notice the difference.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p>Most men do this in reverse. They add creatine first because it's easy — a scoop in a shake, done. Then they wonder why the results don't match the marketing. The supplement didn't fail them. The sequence did.</p>

