      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Should men over 40 take creatine?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — creatine is one of the most well-researched supplements available and has real benefits for men over 40, including improved strength, recovery, and cognitive function. However, it works as a multiplier on an already solid foundation. Men eating less than 100g of protein daily will see far greater benefit from fixing their protein first.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">How much creatine should men over 40 take?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">3–5g of creatine monohydrate per day, taken consistently. No loading phase is necessary — daily supplementation reaches muscle saturation within 3–4 weeks. Creatine monohydrate is the most studied form and outperforms no other form despite costing far less.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Does creatine help with brain function after 40?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">Yes — the brain uses creatine as an energy reserve, and levels decline with age. A 2023 meta-analysis found creatine supplementation improved memory in healthy adults, with larger effects in older adults. For men over 40 noticing mental fatigue or slower recall, this is a legitimate research-backed benefit.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-q">Can creatine replace protein for building muscle?</div>
        <div class="faq-a">No — they serve completely different functions. Protein provides the amino acids muscles use to repair and grow. Creatine enhances the energy system that powers training effort. Without adequate protein, there is no raw material for muscle repair regardless of creatine intake. Fix protein first, then add creatine.</div>
